  <static seed="1578" source="Contrib/PCC/BasicAlgebra/RationalEquations/solveRationalEquations3.pg">
    <statement><p>Solve the equation.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{ {\frac{r+1}{5r-9}} = \frac{3}{8} }</m></p>
<p><fillin characters="34" name="AnSwEr0001"/></p>
</statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>\left\{5\right\}</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution><p>To get rid of all fractions in this equation, we multiple all terms with the common denominator. In this equation, the common denominator is <m>{8\mathopen{}\left(5r-9\right)}</m>.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\begin{aligned}
   {\frac{r+1}{5r-9}} \amp = \frac{3}{8} \\
   {\frac{r+1}{5r-9}} \cdot {8\mathopen{}\left(5r-9\right)} \amp = \frac{3}{8} \cdot {8\mathopen{}\left(5r-9\right)} \\
   8(r+1) \amp = 3(5r - 9) \\
   8r+8 \amp = 15r - 27 \\
   8r+8  \mathbf{-15r-8} \amp = 15r - 27 \mathbf{-15r-8}  \\
   -7r \amp = -35 \\
   \frac{-7r}{-7} \amp = \frac{-35}{-7} \\
   r \amp = 5
\end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
<p>We must check solutions when we solve rational equations. By the original equation, the domain condition is <m>{8\mathopen{}\left(5r-9\right)} \ne 0</m>, or <m>r \ne \frac{9}{5}</m>. This doesn<rsq/>t conflict with the solution above, so the solution is <m>r = 5</m>.</p>
</solution>
